node.text:
Do you have what it takes to become a BARK ranger at Joshua Tree National Park? Watch this video to find out! BARK stands for: 
Bag your poop 
Always wear a leash 
Respect wildlife 
Know where you can go. 
For an audio described version of this video, please see the link in our bio.

node.title: Become a BARK Ranger at Joshua Tree National Park

Thinking of hiking with your four-legged friend? Learn some tips on how to be #DesertReady in today’s ranger moment on hiking with pets. 

Please remember that dogs are not permitted on trails. Pets must be leashed at all times and remain within 100 feet of a roadway (dirt or paved), picnic area, or campground.

For an audio described version of Hiking with Pets, please visit our YouTube channel, or see the link in our bio.

node.text:
As the sun goes down on another beautiful day in Joshua Tree National Park, let's stop to talk about the environmental factors that combine to create a sunset.

Sunsets are impacted by the amount of particulate matter, smog, and humidity in the air. Depending on the combination of these factors, as well as clouds, haze, and other environmental factors, each sunset will produce a unique colloration and appearance.
 
NPS / Emily Hassell

node.accessibility_caption: A Joshua tree against a glowing sunset sky with hues of orange and yellow, a large boulder pile, and a Joshua tree forest.

node.text: Setting the mood right this Sunday ☀  NPS / Alessandra Puig-Santana

node.accessibility_caption: Two people look at a map in the foreground, Joshua trees in the background.

node.text:
This small piece of folded paper could mean the difference between life and death.

Hiking in Joshua Tree National Park this summer? In addition to bringing plenty of water and food for your trek, a trail map is absolutely critical. Getting lost in the park can quickly become a dangerous situation any time of year but is especially dire in summer. The risk of death is much higher this time of year if you get lost in the park due to the high temperatures and fewer people.

What can you do to have a safe hike?

+ Obtain a trail map in advance of your trip, available for free download on our park website at www.nps.gov/JOTR. Or, pick up a map at a park visitor center upon your arrival. 

+ Familiarize yourself with the area in which you’ll be hiking. 

+ Take the opportunity to talk with a ranger about your plan. Ask questions and ensure you have the needed supplies, time, and stamina to complete your hike safely.

+ Stay on marked trails, hike with a partner, and let someone know when and where you plan to hike.

+ And, of course…bring a map with you on the trail!

#SummerSafety
 
Photo: NPS / Kelsey Graczyk

node.accessibility_caption: Rain falls on the Pinto Basin

node.text:
Always be prepared! Summer means dry, hot weather at Joshua Tree, but it’s also the season that brings monsoon rains. These rainstorms come quickly and can produce dangerous flash flood conditions. Remember to always check weather forecasts ahead of your visit and to never drive or wade through flood waters. Turning around can be a decision that saves your life! #SummerSafety
Photo NPS / Brad Sutton

node.text:
Little known fact: 110% of balloons released in Southern California land in Joshua Tree. 

We regularly find balloons littered in the park. They can have a negative impact on our desert ecosystem. For example, the threatened desert tortoise population will sometimes mistake balloons for a food source. Please be careful not to release balloons into the atmosphere. And if you see a balloon in the park, please carry it out with you. We (and the desert tortoises) will appreciate it. 🐢💚 

NPS / Shay Spatz

node.text:
Oh look, a horse tooth fossil. Did you know Joshua Tree was once home to horses, camels, llamas, bison, pronghorn, dire wolves, saber-toothed cats, giant ground sloths, and Columbian mammoths? 

These species lived in Joshua Tree during the Pleistocene Epoch, an era that lasted from 2.6 million to 11,700 years ago. Joshua Tree was not a desert back then. It had lakes, rivers, and more lush vegetation. At the end of the Pleistocene, the climate became warmer and drier and animal species were forced to adapt, migrate, or perish. Some species stayed in Joshua Tree like the desert tortoise, badgers, and pronghorn (until the early 1900’s). Many of the species likely went extinct due to major changes in the climate and the introduction of human hunters. 

All of the fossils shown were excavated in Joshua Tree National Park. 

Photo 1: A fossilized horse tooth (Equus). Photo: Eric Scott
Photo 2: A foot bone from an ancient llama (Hemiauchenia). Photo: Eric Scott
Photo 3: A camel jaw (Camelops). Photo: Eric Scott 
Photo 4: Molars and a tusk fragment from a Columbian mammoth (Mammuthus columbi). NPS / Marker Marshall

Would you still hike in Joshua Tree if all these species existed today?

It’s monsoon season here in Joshua Tree. These rare and short-lived storms can bring heavy amounts of rainfall with them. Be prepared for brilliant lightning storms and raging flash floods.  If you see a river on the road, it’s best to not drive straight into it and destroy your vehicle. If you can't read the depth, it’s likely because it's deep enough to sweep you away. Simply turn around and safely drive away or find higher ground and wait for the storm to pass. Your high-school driving instructor will be proud of your good decision-making. 

🎥 @dannerbird
